        Utilize the LoginContext.
        LoginContext provides the mechanism for invoking the appropriate LoginModule in JAAS. Once the JAAS configuration is loaded, the application must specify which configuration is to be used by JAAS. After LoginContext is utilized, use the login() function to invoke the JAAS authentication procedure. Example:
      LoginContext auth = new LoginContext("AppLoginConfig", new CallbackHandler()); ... auth.login();



        Implement the LoginModule. The LoginModule provides the mechanism used when authenticating users. It is responsible for authenticating and assigning security tokens to the users. 



        Implement the security token. JAAS assigns security tokens to authenticated users. The security tokens must implement the Principal interface. For example:
      import java.security.Principal;public final class UserToken implements Principal, java.io.Serializable{      private String name;      public UserToken(String name)      {            if(name == null)            {                  // A good place to log error                  throw new NullPointerException("Invalid token name.");            }            this.name = name;      }      public String getName()      {            return name;      }      public String toString()      {            return ("UserToken: " + name);      }      public boolean equals(Object o)      {            if(o == null)                      return false;            if(this == o)                      return true;            if(!(o instanceof UserToken))                      return false;            UserToken temp = (UserToken)o;            return this.getName().equals(temp.getName());      }      public int hashCode()      {            return name.hashCode();      }}



        Implement the CallbackHandler. As the link between the user interface and JAAS, the CallbackHandler is the mechanism used when providing user-supplied credentials to JAAS.
